The desert is fun when the sun is out. Everything feels empty, but in a safe and simple way. No people around
to bother you, no cell service to notify you of your responsibilities, just you and your friends and the sand.
That's what we were hoping to find on that Saturday afternoon, as we sat powerless in Riley's car watching
the speedometer continue moving up. Riley was a rally racer, or, at least he wanted to be one. He liked to drive
fast, especially during turns, even the blind ones. We had about an hour left of the drive and we were starting
to relax as we thought of the fun we'd have that day with the shooting gear we were bringing. We had plenty of
targets and ammunition, enough for the four of us, and two guns, and the car. The roads continued to unwind
before us as we drew closer to the vast emptiness of the approaching desert. I didn't know Riley too well, but
it seemed like my friends trusted him well enough. The air conditioning in his car was broken so we had the
windows down and the warm air felt good on our faces, or at least mine. The plan was simple: we'd get to the
spot, set up targets, shoot for a bit, and be home for dinner. Nothing felt dangerous.

Once we were within about 30 minutes of our spot, all of our cell service dropped. No more texting my family
how close we were, no more music, just the sound of the wind and the light of the sun. Riley told us that he
wanted to go off-roading. We could tell he knew what he was doing, so we let him. Things were scary for a little,
but once we came to a stop at the end I had no regrets. So far the day was going great, just as we had planned.
About 10 minutes later we had arrived. We all sloshed out of the car and rushed to stretch our legs after two
hours straight of nothing but driving. 

"Everybody grab a target, we don't have all day."\
We began setting up to shoot. We set up our targets against a dry hillside and spent the next few hours shooting.
For some of us it was their first time ever holding a gun, but I already knew how to shoot from Boy Scouts so I
waited to go last with Riley. We could hear echoes of other people doing what we were, but we never managed to
actually see anyone. We were talking about our new college lives, the latest relationship drama with one of our
friends who wasn't there, the usual stuff of friends. I could already tell it would be a day I would never
forget.

"I'd say we have about 20 minutes before sunset."\
We got the gear back into the car, reluctantly slouched back into our seats, and started driving.

About 20 minutes later, Riley suggested we go off-roading again to mess around for a bit. It didn't feel like
a choice, we were already speeding up. We found a cool car trail off to the left at a slight angle and took it.
Our tires fit nicely into the well-worn tire tracks beneath us. We drifted and turned, spewing dirt all around
us, only to find our way back to the tire tracks. We knew if we stayed on the tracks we'd eventually find the
main road again. We kept checking the gas levels to see how far we could go before turning back, but we seemed
to be fine. By this point the sun had gone well below the horizon, and the light had faded out completely.

"Can we head back now? I wanna see if I can get some service."\
Riley made a hard right to start heading back in the direction we thought the main road was in. This trail was
bumpier, but we knew we were safe because of the obvious tire tracks from people before us. We were plowing
over small bushes, testing the limits of Riley's suspension in every way possible, just like he wanted.

That right turn was the moment everything started feeling off. The headlights seemed like they were getting
narrower, but it was probably just in my head. Our car was carving its way through a seemingly endless darkness
with nothing but two beams of hope. Then the car sank. We skidded violently to a sudden and unplanned stop.
Silence. Nobody spoke. Nobody knew what to say. It was pitch black. Gas was limited. No communication with the
rest of the world, not even our parents. All that was left was the sound of our loosely spinning tires. Then the
doors started opening. Flashlights swarmed.

"Looks like all the weight's on the undercarriage."\
The same tire tracks that were guiding us towards safety had us trapped. The tires could no longer reach the
ground. We tried pushing the car, nothing happened.

"I guess now we dig."\
And dig we did. The wind was cold and sharp. None of us had prepared for the relentlessness of that cold. We
quickly realized it would take hours to dig it out with our bare hands, so Riley and I began looking for
shovel-shaped rocks to give the group. We continued digging, but it was hard to tell if any of it was working.
The bottom of the car was hot from all the revving we had done to initially try to back out. On another trip
looking for rocks, I saw headlights. Or at least I thought I had, but they had already vanished. Then they
came back. It looked like another car was driving on the main road in the direction we were headed, but they
were already almost past where we must have turned off, and were about to start getting further away.

Riley didn't hesitate. He took off toward the headlights before any of us could argue. He was gone, out of sight,
with no phone, in the black desert. We had no choice but to keep digging as the headlights faded away. Our witty
side conversations slowed to a halt as we all began to realize that Riley had taken the keys with him.\
Alone.\
Another 10 minutes passed. There was still plenty of digging to keep us distracted, but we were starting to lose
hope. Then suddenly, the headlights flashed again. We could tell they were far, but at least someone was still
out there. The lights inched along in my field of vision. It seemed like they were getting closer. Then suddenly
they turned. They were pointing right at us. We waited anxiously, still having seen no sign of Riley. The car
became more visible, it appeared to be some sort of Jeep, perfect for towing, assuming that was its reason for
coming towards us. I grabbed a gun and hid it under our car near me. Then we saw what we had all been silently
hoping for, Riley was in the front seat. We heard dogs barking fiercely. The man seemed to be in his late 40s,
and appeared to be alone aside from Riley and... his dogs? They stopped in front of us and got out of the car.
We watched as Riley, without a word, began hooking our car to the man's. The man was too busy controlling his
dogs to acknowledge us. Once the car was hooked up, we all got in and began sliding backwards loudly. The noise
stopped. We were free. We graciously thanked the man for coming out of his way to help us, as we all knew what
could've happened without him.

The drive home was a quiet one. I think we were all still recovering from the adrenaline. We all jumped as the
music suddenly started blasting as we got service and all of our phones started to catch up with all of the day's
notifications. We made it back to civilization and, eventually, back home. The desert is fun when the sun is out.
After dark, it’s something else entirely.
